  "prompt": "How does a half moon happen?",
  "response": "A half moon occurs during the lunar cycle when exactly half of the moon's illuminated surface is visible from Earth. This happens during two specific phases of the moon:\n\n1. First Quarter Moon: When the right half of the moon appears illuminated (as seen from the Northern Hemisphere)\n\n2. Last Quarter Moon: When the left half of the moon appears illuminated (as seen from the Northern Hemisphere)\n\nThese phases happen because of the moon's position relative to the Earth and Sun. As the moon orbits Earth, different portions of its surface are illuminated by sunlight:\n\n- The moon reflects sunlight from its surface\n- Its position in orbit determines how much of the illuminated surface we can see\n- When the moon is at a 90-degree angle from the Sun relative to Earth, half of its visible surface is lit\n\nEach half moon phase occurs about a week after the new moon and a week before the next new moon, representing a quarter of the complete lunar cycle.\n\nThe half moon is part of the moon's waxing and waning process, which takes approximately 29.5 days to complete a full cycle from new moon back to new moon.",
